<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ881019-0018 </DOCNO><HL> International: Japan's Consumers Boosted Spending 3.2% in August </HL><AUTHOR> (WSJ Special) </AUTHOR><SO> </SO><CO> JAPAN </CO><DATELINE> TOKYO  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Consumer spending in Japan rose an inflation-adjusted 3.2% in August from a year earlier, continuing an increase that has become an important engine of growth for the nation's economy.    The August increase was the fifth this year of 3% or more, and consumer spending hasn't declined in 18 months. Outlays in the latest month were boosted by a 10% increase in spending on entertainment and leisure, reflecting a trend toward more leisure time for Japanese workers.    Among other sectors, spending on housing rose 3.5% and education outlays increased 5%. Spending on food was up 0.4%. The inflation-adjusted income of wage-earning Japanese families, meanwhile, increased 3.2%. </TEXT></DOC>